Street, Shepherd Park neighborhood,

01:00:03.690 --> 01:00:05.120
elementary school, etcetera.

01:00:05.120 --> 01:00:06.420
&gt;&gt; John Richardson: Oh, yes; yes.

01:00:06.420 --> 01:00:07.720
Yes, I lived there; yes.

01:00:07.720 --> 01:00:10.010
&gt;&gt; Speaker 8: Why was
that area picked?

01:00:10.010 --> 01:00:13.510
&gt;&gt; John Richardson: Well, because
you saw the picture of Bleak House.

01:00:13.510 --> 01:00:19.840
Bleak House was part of a
230-acre piece of ground

01:00:19.840 --> 01:00:23.810
that Shepherd bought in 1867.

01:00:23.810 --> 01:00:27.850
And then they built Bleak
House and they used it as sort

01:00:27.850 --> 01:00:29.170
of an out-of-town residence.

01:00:29.170 --> 01:00:34.020
But that -- so that's why
-- and there was a long,

01:00:34.020 --> 01:00:39.480
winding road that went out to a
guard house or a porter's house.

01:00:39.480 --> 01:00:44.080
In fact, if any of you know
James Goode's, "Capital Losses,"

01:00:44.080 --> 01:00:47.530
a wonderful book showing
buildings that no longer exist

01:00:47.530 --> 01:00:49.050 position:56%
in Washington and what is there now.

01:00:49.050 --> 01:00:52.990
And it shows the porter's
lodge at 7th Street Road.

01:00:52.990 --> 01:00:56.930
But that, anyhow -- so Bleak House
was part of that 200-acre piece

01:00:56.930 --> 01:01:01.770
of ground where they built it,
north of Walter Reed Hospital.

01:01:01.770 --> 01:01:06.460
And I lived there for 15 years,
very close to Bleak House.

01:01:06.460 --> 01:01:10.510
Okay, I think, Pam, you want
-- alright; thank you all.

